<body lang=EN-US style='text-justify-trim:punctuation'>

<div class=Section1>

<h1><span style='font-size:10.5pt;font-family:"Lucida Sans Unicode"'>CSCI 331 -
Software Systems                                                                                </span></h1>

<h3><span style='font-size:10.5pt'>PROGRAM 1</span></h3> 
<h3>PROJECT COLLABORATION TYPE:  <u>Individual</u>.<BR>
	That means you should do the work on your own. <br>
	(<i>However, you may discuss with others</i>)</h3>

<p>
<h2>THE PROGRAM:</h2>  This is the first and foundational 
installment of the object-oriented programming (OOP) project for this class.
It is modeled after the project described in the text book.
You will need to use the results of this project in subsequent projects so do
this one carefully and design for change since you will certainly want to
change what you do here.
</p>

<ol>
    <li>Design a class <b>Book</b>.
    <br>Each object represents information about a single book.
    <br>Members should include:
    <ul>
	<li> Mandatory Fields
	<ul>
	    <li>identification number
	    <li> author<small>(s)</small> (<i>or editor<small>(s)</small></i>)
	    <li> title
	    <li> publisher
	    <li> year
	</ul>
	<li> Optional Fields
	<ul>
	    <li> volume
	    <li> series
	    <li> address
	    <li> edition
	    <li> month
	    <li> note
	</ul>
    </ul>


    <br>Methods should include:

    <ul>
	<li>constructors
	<li>destructors
	<li>assignment (<i>overloaded </i><b><tt>'='</tt></b> <i>operator</i>)
	<li>mutators (<i>allow modification of each respective field</i>)
	<li>accessors (<i>allow change-free access to each respective field</i>)
	<li>dump (<i>for debugging</i>)
    </ul>

    <li>Design a class <b>Person</b>.
    <br>Each object represents information about a single person.
    <br>Members should include
    <ul>
	<li>identification number
	<li>first name
	<li>last name
    </ul>
    <br>Methods should include
    <ul>
	<li>constructors 
	<li>destructors
	<li>assignment
	<li>mutators
	<li>accessors
	<li>dump
    </ul>

    <li>Design a class <b>Lending</b>.
    <br>Each object represents a person borrowing one or more copies of a
	certain book.
    <br>Members should include</span></p>
    <ul>
	<li><u>person</u> identification number
	<li><u>book</u> identification number
	<li> the number of copies borrowed
    </ul>

    <br>Methods should include
    <ul>
	<li>constructors 
	<li>destructors
	<li>assignment
	<li>mutators
	<li>accessors
	<li>dump
    </ul>
</ol>


<ul>
    <li>Implement your classes and create lists of <u>books</u>,
    <u>persons</u>, and <u>lendings</u>.
    <ul>
	<li>This will be used in subsequent programming projects.
    </ul>
    <li>Add methods to the classes to read field values from an input stream
    and to write the fields of an object to an output stream nicely formatted.
    <li>You may also want to be able to prompt a user to enter the field values.
    <li>Use the C++ stream operations to implement these methods.
    <li>Write a driver program to verify that the class along with its
    methods is correctly implemented.
</ul>

<p>
<h2>WHAT TO TURN IN:</h2>
Each of the items below should be typeset on a separate page.
All the pages must be stapled together so that we can read everything without
taking the staple out.

<ol>
    <li><u>Design document for the classes</u>.<br>
    This one doesn’t have to be typed but it must be drawn neatly.<br>
    Use only one side of the paper and do not hand in pages
    torn from a spiral notebook unless you cut off the ruffles.<br>
    (<font color="teal">25% of your grade</font>)

    <li> <u>The test data used</u>,<br>
    along with an <u>explanation of why you chose it</u>,<br>
    and <u>what were the results of the tests</u>.<br>
    This should include a script file from the test runs.<br>
    Each test should be annotated on the script file.<br>
    (<font color="teal">25% of your grade</font>)

    <li><u>The source file of the program</u>.<br>
    Also, leave a copy of the source file in your account until the graded
    program is returned to you.<br>
    (<font color="teal">20% of your grade</font>)

    <li><u>The users manual</u>.<br>
    This should be typed and have a section for each of the following:<br>
    (<font color="teal">25% of your grade</font>)
    <ol type=a>
	<li>The name of the program.
	<li>What the program is supposed to do.
	<li>Where it is located on the computer.<br>
	(<tt>pwd</tt> will answer this for you)
	<li>How to run the program.
	<li>A sample execution of the program.<br>
	(this is not the test data)
	<li>What the known errors in the program are.
	<li>A short paragraph describing what you learned from this assignment.
    </ol>
	<li>Try to answer the questions:
	<br>(<font color="teal">5% of your grade</font>)
    <ul>
	<li>How much time did you spend on the program?
	<li>Did you plan well before going to the computer?
	<li>Did you test the program completely? 
	<li>Did you learn anything new about the language?
	<li>Did you learn anything new about the way you study or should study?
    </ul>
</ol>

</div>

